          "body": "Ezekiel 7 stands in a long line of Day-of-the-LORD oracles: Amos 5:18-20 (Israel will find the day darkness, not light), Isaiah 13 (the day comes with wrath and burning anger), Zephaniah 1:14-18 (the great day is near, neither silver nor gold will deliver — the precise vocabulary of Ezekiel 7:19). Joel 2:1-2 uses the same near-trumpet-no-escape structure. The New Testament picks up this trajectory in 2 Thessalonians 1:7-10 (the Lord Jesus revealed with mighty angels in flaming fire, rendering recompense) and Revelation 6:15-17 (kings, military leaders, and wealthy throw themselves behind rocks, asking who can stand before the wrath of the Lamb — an unmistakable echo of Ezekiel 7:17-19). Ezekiel 7 is not an isolated oracle of doom but the Old Testament's most concentrated articulation of a canonical pattern: covenantal sin accumulates to a terminus, the Day arrives with inescapable comprehensiveness, every human refuge fails, and the purpose of it all is that the LORD becomes known. The New Testament does not soften this pattern; it escalates it to eschatological scale and names the agent of final judgment as the One who was pierced for iniquity rather than destroyed by it."
